The Telegraph - Calcutta : Opinion
		 Friday, January 23, 2004 							 																						BETWEEN IMAGE AND VIEWER																														VIDEO ART IN INDIA (Apeejay, price not mentioned) showcases a number of contemporary artists  mostly Indian  whose work in video installation and animation have been shown at New Delhis modernist glass-and-steel Apeejay Media Gallery. The book is impressively put together, with curatorial and historical introductions, and lavish photographs which cannot, however, capture the full impact of this arts complex technological feats. The critical regionalism of Indian video art often tends to load the encounter between image and viewer with an unpleasure, a discomfort. But it is impossible not to feel that this art form, in India at least, remains palpably thrilled with its own newness, and has already accrued around itself its own post-modernist jargon. This is a still from Nalini Malanis video installation with sound, Hamletmachine (2000), which explores the rise of Hindu fundamentalists in India
